# S3 Basics – Overview

S3 in nutshell is a storage service provided by amazon. User can simply create the bucket and use it to store files and other objects, also S3 provides developers and IT teams with secure, durable, highly-scalable object storage for things like static website hosting and pace to store all the required files that need regular access for the functioning of the programs.  Amazon S3 is easy to use, with simple web services interface to store and retrieve any amount of data from anywhere on the web.

Few important points to remember

- S3 is Object based i.e. allows you to upload files
- S3 is a safe place to store your files.
- The data is spread across multiple devices and facilities.
- Files can be from 0 Bytes to 5 TB
- There is unlimited storage
- Files are stored in Buckets
- S3 is a universal namespace, that is, names must be unique globally.

# Creating a Bucket with S3

1. 1.Connect to AWS console

Click on [https://aws.amazon.com/](https://aws.amazon.com/)  to connect with Console, Click on Sign in to console.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Once you sign in to console, you will be able to see below screen

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Now select Services and in Storage you will find S3 as one of the Storage. Click on S3 under storage.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Once you click on S3 under Storage, You will land up on below page –

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. 2.Create a Bucket

Click on create bucket, Remember this Bucket name is always Universal and unique. We can access a bucket by using DNS. Now when we click on Create a bucket, we will land on below popup.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

We can just click on Create and can exit from this popup at this stage, but it is preferred to make all the settings following next tabs.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

When we press next, below screen will appear. Here we can set the properties-

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Here we can set the Tags, can control versioning or we can set the server access.

Now press on Next to set the permissions, below screen will appear-

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Here on Set Permission tab. Since I am the owner of this bucket, I am having all kinds of access to this bucket –

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

We can add users and grant them Read/Write access from below section of Permission tab

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In below tab, we can manage public permissions and system level permissions

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Click Next and move on to Review tab, here we can validate all the settings done in Prior steps. After validation is completed now you can click on Create Bucket. Bucket will be visible in our console now.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

1. 3.Upload files in Bucket

To upload the files in bucket, click on created bucket. Below screen will appear –



 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Click on Upload button for uploading files-

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

After adding files, click on Upload. File is visible now in our bucket-

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Now we will try to open this file, click on file in overview section a link will be visible as below, click on Link.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

An error will appear as &quot;Access Denied&quot;, as below-

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The reason for above error is the File is Private and not Public. Select your file, and click on More and then click on &quot;Mark Public&quot; as below-

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Once you make it public you will be able to see this file.
